### Exception Handling in C#

Exceptions represent runtime errors that disrupt normal program flow. C# provides structured exception handling using try-catch-finally.

### What are Exceptions?

```csharp
// Example exceptions
int.Parse("abc");      // FormatException
int[] arr = new int[3];
arr[10] = 5;           // IndexOutOfRangeException
object obj = null;
obj.ToString();        // NullReferenceException
```

### Exception Hierarchy

```
System.Exception
  +-- System.SystemException
  |     +-- System.ArgumentException
  |     +-- System.IndexOutOfRangeException
  |     +-- System.NullReferenceException
  |     +-- System.InvalidOperationException
  +-- System.IO.IOException
  +-- System.Data.DataException
```

### Common Exception Types

| Exception | Cause |
|-----------|-------|
| `NullReferenceException` | Accessing null object member |
| `IndexOutOfRangeException` | Index outside array bounds |
| `ArgumentException` | Invalid method argument |
| `ArgumentNullException` | Null argument when not expected |
| `FormatException` | Invalid string format for parsing |
| `InvalidOperationException` | Operation invalid in current state |
| `IOException` | I/O error (file not found, etc.) |
| `DivideByZeroException` | Division by zero |
| `OverflowException` | Arithmetic overflow |

### Exception Properties

```csharp
try
{
    // Code that may throw
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    Console.WriteLine(ex.Message);       // Human-readable description
    Console.WriteLine(ex.StackTrace);    // Call stack at throw point
    Console.WriteLine(ex.InnerException); // Wrapped exception
    Console.WriteLine(ex.Source);        // Application name
}
```

### Throwing Exceptions

```csharp
throw new ArgumentException("Value must be positive");

// Conditional throw
if (age < 0)
    throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException(nameof(age), "Age cannot be negative");

// Throw with inner exception
throw new ApplicationException("Something failed", innerException);
```

### Best Practices

| Practice | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| Catch specific types | Avoid catching `Exception` broadly |
| Don't swallow exceptions | Log or re-throw |
| Use finally for cleanup | Close files, connections |
| Throw early, catch late | Let callers handle errors |
| Use meaningful messages | Help debugging |
| Don't use exceptions for flow | Use if-else for expected cases |

### Re-throwing Exceptions

```csharp
try { Process(); }
catch (Exception ex)
{
    LogError(ex);
    throw;          // Preserve original stack trace
    // throw ex;    // Reset stack trace (bad)
}
```

> **Key Point:** Exceptions are for exceptional, unexpected errors. Don't use them for regular control flow. Always clean up resources in `finally` blocks. Catch the most specific exception type possible. Use `throw;` (not `throw ex;`) to preserve the original stack trace.

### When to Throw

```csharp
public void SetAge(int age)
{
    if (age < 0 || age > 150)
        throw new ArgumentOutOfRangeException(nameof(age), "Age must be 0-150");
    this.age = age;
}
```

### Filtering with when

```csharp
try { }
catch (HttpException ex) when (ex.StatusCode == 404)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Not found");
}
catch (HttpException ex) when (ex.StatusCode == 500)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Server error");
}

codeExample:
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        try
        {
            Console.Write("Enter a number: ");
            int number = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());
            int result = 100 / number;
            Console.WriteLine($"100 / {number} = {result}");
        }
        catch (DivideByZeroException)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Cannot divide by zero");
        }
        catch (FormatException)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Invalid number format");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"Error: {ex.Message}");
        }
    }
}
